<div xmlns:perseus="http://www.perseus.org/meta/perseus.rdfs#" xmlns:dctype="http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/" xmlns:tufts="http://www.tufts.edu/" xmlns:alph="http://alpheios.net/namespaces/tei" class="alpheios-lex-text_container en">
    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n1822" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">βασιλεύς</span></b> , <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ῆος</span>: <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">king</span>, exercising the
          functions of commander - in - chief, priest, and judge; pl., <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">βασιλῆες</span>, <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">kings, nobles,
            chiefs</span>, termed <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">σκηπτοῦχοι, διογενεῖς,
            διοτρεφεῖς</span>.—Used adjectively w. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἀνήρ,</span>
          <i><span class="en">Il. 3.170</span></i>; <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">
            ἄναξ</span>, <i><span class="en">Od. 20.194</span></i>; hence
          comp. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">βασιλεύτερος</span>, sup. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">βασιλεύτατος</span>, <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">more, most kingly,
            princely.</span>
        </div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
    <div class="alpheios-lex-alph-source">From <u>
            <u>A Homeric Dictionary</u>
        </u> (Georg Autenrieth, New York, Harper and Brothers, 1891) </div>
